ChatGPT said:

This is not a React or JSX problem. It is a text-formatting issue caused by how the code was copied and pasted.

What is actually happening

The code you pasted does not contain real line breaks (\n).
Instead, it contains spaces between tokens where line breaks should be.

So VS Code is behaving correctly:

  • Since there are no newline characters, it renders the entire file as one long logical line

  • That is why you see a straight line across the editor

Example from your paste (simplified):

js
import React , { useRef , useState } from 'react' ;

This looks multiline visually in the chat, but internally it is:

javascript
importReact,{useRef,useState}from'react';

No Enter characters exist.

Why this usually happens

This occurs when code is copied from:

  • Rich-text editors

  • PDFs

  • Some chat interfaces

  • Formatted web pages

  • Copy buttons that preserve layout visually but not actual newlines

ChatGPT messages, in particular, can visually wrap lines without inserting real line breaks.

How to confirm this in VS Code

  1. Click anywhere in the file

  2. Press End

  3. Notice the cursor goes extremely far to the right

  4. Press Enter once suddenly the line breaks

That confirms it was a single logical line.

How to fix it (properly)

Option 1: Auto-format (recommended)

  1. Ensure the file is saved as .jsx

  2. Select all code: Ctrl + A

  3. Format:

    • Shift + Alt + F (Windows)

    • or right-click Format Document

This works only if Prettier or a formatter is installed.

Option 2: Use Format Selection

If full format fails:

  • Select all

  • Right-click Format Selection

Option 3: Paste as plain text (future-proof)

When pasting:

  • Use Ctrl + Shift + V (Paste as plain text)

Or paste into:

  • Notepad first

  • Then copy again into VS Code

Important note about your code quality

Your JSX and logic are structurally valid.
This issue has nothing to do with errors in your component, ViewShot usage, template literals, or Expo APIs.

Once properly formatted, the code will:

  • Indent correctly

  • Regain syntax highlighting

  • Stop appearing as one long line

One additional observation (not related, but important)

You are using:

js
import { useThem } from 'constants/useTheme'

This is likely a typo and should be:

js
import { useTheme } from 'constants/useTheme'

If left unchanged, it will cause a runtime error, but againthis is unrelated to the straight line issue.

Summary

  • VS Code is not broken

  • JSX is not broken

  • Your code was pasted without newline characters

  • Auto-formatting will immediately fix it

This is a very common issue and not a mistake on your part.

You said:
i am using js, but the code was in jsx
ChatGPT said:

That clarification actually explains the behavior very clearly.

What is happening

You pasted JSX code into a .js file, and the code you copied already had its line breaks stripped.
So two things are occurring at the same time:

  1. The pasted text contains no real newline characters

  2. The file is .js, not .jsx, so VS Code does not fully parse it as JSX

The result is exactly what you are seeing:
VS Code renders everything as one long line (straight line) and formatting does not behave as expected.

Why .js vs .jsx matters here

JSX is not valid plain JavaScript syntax unless a parser (Babel / TypeScript / ESLint) knows to expect JSX.

When the file is named:

  • VerificationSlip.js
    VS Code assumes standard JavaScript

  • VerificationSlip.jsx
    VS Code enables JSX grammar + formatting rules

When JSX is pasted into a .js file without line breaks, VS Code cannot safely infer formatting boundaries, so it leaves it as-is.

The correct fix (do this in order)

1. Rename the file to .jsx

In VS Code:

  • Right-click the file

  • Rename:

text
VerificationSlip.jsx

This alone fixes syntax recognition.

2. Reformat the document

Now run:

  • Windows: Shift + Alt + F

  • Mac: Shift + Option + F

or:

  • Right-click Format Document

VS Code (or Prettier) will now:

  • Reinsert proper line breaks

  • Indent JSX correctly

  • Restore readability

If formatting still doesnt work

That means the pasted text truly has zero newline characters.

Do this once:

  1. Place the cursor anywhere

  2. Press Enter

  3. Select all (Ctrl + A)

  4. Format again

Best practice going forward

You have two clean options:

Option A (recommended)

Keep JSX components as:

components/
  VerificationSlip.jsx

Option B

If you insist on .js, ensure your project has:

  • Babel configured for JSX

  • ESLint / Prettier enabled

But even then, .jsx is clearer and avoids this exact confusion.

Key takeaway

This was not a React error, not a VS Code bug, and not bad code.

It was:

  • JSX pasted into a .js file

  • With line breaks stripped during copy

Once the file is .jsx and formatted, everything will behave normally.

Your current Prettier configuration is already good, but it is incomplete for a modern React / React Native / Expo codebase. Below is a production-grade Prettier configuration that is widely used in professional teams and works very well with JS, JSX, React Native, and Expo.

I will first show the recommended config, then explain why each option exists, and finally point out what was missing from yours.

RECOMMENDED PRETTIER CONFIG (BEST PRACTICE)

json
{
  "semi": true,
  "singleQuote": true,
  "jsxSingleQuote": false,
  "trailingComma": "all",
  "bracketSpacing": true,
  "bracketSameLine": false,
  "arrowParens": "always",
  "printWidth": 100,
  "tabWidth": 2,
  "useTabs": false,
  "endOfLine": "lf"
}

This setup is:

  • Stable across Windows / macOS

  • Clean for JSX

  • Ideal for React Native UI files

  • Team-friendly and diff-friendly

WHY EACH SETTING MATTERS

semi: true

Keeps explicit semicolons
Avoids edge-case ASI bugs
Common in enterprise JS

singleQuote: true

Cleaner JavaScript strings
Matches React Native community norms

jsxSingleQuote: false

JSX attributes use double quotes

jsx
<View style={styles.container} />

This is the most readable JSX convention.

trailingComma: "all" (important upgrade)

Cleaner git diffs
Easier reordering of props
Fully supported by modern JS

Example:

js
const obj = {
  a: 1,
  b: 2,
};

bracketSpacing: true

Standard readability:

js
{ data, loading }

bracketSameLine: false

JSX closing brackets stay on new lines:

jsx
<Component
  prop1="value"
  prop2="value"
>

This is much clearer in React Native layouts.

arrowParens: "always"

Avoids ambiguity
Matches your existing preference

printWidth: 100 (critical for React Native)

Prevents JSX props from becoming unreadable
80 is too tight for mobile UI code

tabWidth: 2

Industry standard
Matches ESLint defaults

useTabs: false

Avoids editor inconsistencies
Spaces are predictable everywhere

endOfLine: "lf" (very important on Windows)

Prevents Git line-ending noise
Avoids cross-platform formatting churn

WHAT YOUR CURRENT CONFIG IS MISSING

Your config:

json
{
  "semi": true,
  "singleQuote": true,
  "trailingComma": "es5",
  "bracketSpacing": true,
  "arrowParens": "always"
}

Missing:

  • printWidth causes ugly wrapping

  • tabWidth inconsistent indentation

  • endOfLine Git diff problems

  • jsxSingleQuote JSX inconsistency

  • bracketSameLine JSX readability

  • trailingComma: "all" better diffs

json

  "extends": ["eslint:recommended", "plugin:react/recommended", "prettier"]
